<div class="card mt-4">
  <div class="card-body">
    <h5 class="card-title">📚 About This Tool</h5>
    <p>
      This tool generates random passphrases using the Diceware method. 
      Each phrase is composed of common, memorable words, making them secure yet easy to recall.
      You can choose how many words are used and what separator (delimiter) appears between them.
    </p>

    <h6>🔐 Why Use Passphrases?</h6>
    <p>
      Unlike complex passwords with random characters, passphrases are made of real words—longer, yet human-readable.
      A passphrase like <code>cat-planet-zebra-fork</code> is easier to remember than <code>j$L4@eX#</code> and often more secure.
    </p>

    <h6>📏 Entropy & Strength Explained</h6>
    <p>
      Entropy quantifies unpredictability. The more entropy, the harder a password is to crack.
      It's calculated as:
    </p>
    <pre>Entropy = L × log₂(N)</pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>L</strong>: Number of words in the passphrase</li>
      <li><strong>N</strong>: Size of the wordlist (e.g., 7776 for Diceware)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      For example, a 6-word passphrase using a 7776-word list has an estimated entropy of 
      <strong>~77 bits</strong>, making it resilient against brute-force attacks.
    </p>

    <h6>🛡️ Password Best Practices</h6>
    <ul>
      <li>Avoid using the same password or passphrase across sites</li>
      <li>Don’t reuse old passwords—even with slight variations</li>
      <li>Use a password manager to securely store long passphrases</li>
      <li>Enable multi-factor authentication wherever possible</li>
      <li>Don't use names, birthdays, or real phrases from books/movies</li>
    </ul>

    <h6>🎲 What is Diceware?</h6>
    <p>
      Diceware is a method where each word in a passphrase is selected by rolling five dice. 
      The resulting 5-digit number is mapped to a word from a 7776-entry list.
      Our tool replicates this process digitally using a secure randomizer.
    </p>

    <h6>🖥️ Offline/Manual Generation Options</h6>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Linux/macOS</strong>: Use <code>/dev/urandom</code> or <code>shuf</code></li>
      <li><strong>Windows</strong>: PowerShell’s <code>Get-Random</code> with a wordlist</li>
      <li><strong>CLI Tools</strong>: Use <code>diceware</code> or <code>pwgen</code></li>
      <li><strong>Password Managers</strong>: KeePass, Bitwarden, 1Password often include generators</li>
      <li><strong>Manual Dice</strong>: Print a Diceware list and roll five 6-sided dice</li>
    </ul>

    <h6>📌 Pro Tip</h6>
    <p>
      Longer passphrases (5–7 words) with diverse delimiters are more secure and easier to type than mixed-case-symbol-number passwords.
    </p>
